TL:DR the American education system sucks major diarrhea dookie asshole for anyone who isn’t cishet and neurotypical 🙃🙃🙃 not that y’all didn’t know that already https://t.co/2Dr0nbasI0

So no, I didn’t go to a fancy million dollar art school because 1.) I’m poor and 2.) I was failed by the American public school system. I graduated with a 2.24 and an ACT score of 18. Guess what bitch? I’m smart as hell AND prettier than you 💅💅

I’ve studied languages, civilizations, architecture, religions, psychology, and so much more to inspire stories and art- something that they don’t have. I’m proud of the knowledge I’ve acquired and will continue to gain.

My sisters both got over 3.0 GPA’s and are so smart and skilled at what they do. Engineering, Robotics, and Music are what THEY’RE best at. But there are things that I know that they don’t because I’m always taking in new information.

No, I’m not hiding behind my diagnosis’ to get away with my GPA. You absolutely should always try your hardest. If you don’t hit your goal, it’s okay because you still made an attempt. But don’t rag on those of us who weren’t lucky enough to have a great academic experience.

But maybe this isn’t your story. Maybe you went to a great school, had a healthy family relationship, and plenty of support and sources to better yourself from a young age.
By all means, do YOUR best... but don’t bring down those of us who hit rough patch after rough patch.

I’m mad that I was treated that way for something that wasn’t- and still isn’t- my fault. I didn’t ask to go undiagnosed and unmedicated. I didn’t ask to be ostracized and abandoned by the people who were supposed to teach me.

Yes, I’m mad that I can’t go back and fix all those years I never succeeded. I’m mad that people made me- a LITERAL CHILD- feel stupid and worthless because I wasn’t as driven as the other kids. But I’m not mad at myself.
But maybe I could have been a straight A student had I been diagnosed much earlier. Maybe I could have been a lawyer or a doctor or whatever.

Every DAY I think about how a specific, CLOSE family member said that I was weak and would never amount to anything... with me in earshot. How the fuck was I supposed to get a 3.0 or anything higher with a living situation like that?

I spent my academic life being bullied by teachers and peers for being different- something that would later be diagnosed as Autism after I’d already entered college. I lacked the energy, concentration, and long term memory due to ADHD... also diagnosed too little too late.

I graduated high school with a 2.24 GPA. An ACT score of 18. A 3/5 on my portfolio review. I still got into college. I still found work. But I did not hit a rough “patch” in life- I LIVED a rough life.
Just unfollowed an artist because they think having a low GPA is just because you “hit a rough patch in life” 😕

Never. Stop. Creating.

There is no right or wrong way to be an artist. Whatever you choose to make with your own two hands is an extension of your innermost self and THAT is what makes me wake up every day and want to create- to show others what *I* see in myself and the world around me.

I’m proud of ALL of my art because it’s those pieces that got me where I am today. From the cringey anime phase, the shitposts, my OC’s AND the fanart I make today. Nothing is going to change that, especially not the opinion of some prick who thinks they’re better than others. https://t.co/q7xpsSABVO

It took a LONG time to figure out how any of this stuff worked. Pieces I was once proud of in the moment seem so distant compared to the progress I’ve made. While it’s still good art, my current self has improved so much that my past art feels so sloppy. (18-19 y/o) https://t.co/ynhFWlztqZ

And those aren’t even my EARLY digital pieces. Digital art is an entirely different medium- its like learning a new language. I had to teach myself how programs worked, what brushes I liked, and how to draw while looking at a screen instead of what my hand was doing. (12-14 y/o) https://t.co/5BIh4EPP9W

4th image are some recent pieces where I’ve been teaching myself how to express emotions through my work. I struggle with showing my own, so drawing what I’m feeling and trying to learn how to convey that in a face that isn’t mine has been a fun challenge.
3rd image is my first piece on proper ADHD meds. It was only a few months ago and even though there are things I’d like to change, I’m still happy with what the piece became.
2nd image is from when I took a break from college. I didn’t make a lot of art in art school surprisingly, but I did use my time to figure out what and how I wanted to draw.

In the first image the blue baseball piece and the flower one are all done in pen. I was 14-16. The pen pieces didn’t have first drafts in pencil, they had to all be done first try in pen for the class and couldn’t be taken home.
